defaultQ95 default&#xa0; 
defaultMark defaultPawseydefault:default Does that make up a large part of your work? No. May I just ask about levels of competency? Is it right that the level of competency to work in an industrial environment should be higher than in a domestic environment? What is your view on that?
defaultEmma Clancy:default It is about appropriateness. For example, for our predominantly commercial scheme known as the approved contractor, it is a whole-day assessment. The assessment takes into account the nature of the work that you are doing. 
defaultQ96 default&#xa0; 
defaultMark defaultPawseydefault:default How would you know that somebody who is only approved to work in a domestic environment is not working on commercial installations? 
defaultEmma Clancy:default We would know whether we had assessed them for that. We would not know whether they were doing that work. What is important from our point of view is that we are only listing for what we have assessed people to be competent to deliver. 
defaultQ97 default&#xa0; 
defaultMark defaultPawseydefault:default How would a system prevent somebody who is only accredited for domestic work from moving over to commercial work without carrying out any further training? Are there any controls on that? 
defaultDavid defaultCowburndefault:default It is not regulated. Only the domestic sector is regulated.
defaultEmma Clancy:default It is only in the domestic sector that it is regulated. Outside of that, it is not. 
defaultDavid defaultCowburndefault:default On a voluntary level, though, the specification that I talked about earlier that covers the domestic sector also covers the commercial sector. You asked about levels, and I am not an expert in education but level 3 is an understood level of qualification. Both for domestic and for industrial work, they are level 3 qualifications. One is a certificate and the other is a diploma, but they are both set at level 3, which means able to work unsupervised. 
defaultQ98 default&#xa0; 
defaultMark defaultPawseydefault:default Right, but you did say that there is no regulation at all in respect of commercial installations. 
